FRENCH COUNTRY WINES

Throughout the year, American tourists happily occupy the better hotels of Paris and the wonderful inns, relais and resorts of the French countryside. What do they drink? In most instances, they will happily imbibe the local wines that are charming, excellent, and are still obtainable at low cost. These ‘country wines’ make no pretense to greatness—each has its own personal message, its own charm, and combines beautifully with the local food specialties.

The better country wines of France have now reached us and they can be enjoyed in America today at delightfully low cost. You need merely look at the list below for convincing evidence.

LOIRE VALLEY WHITE

The Loire River meanders at its own delicious slow pace for 600 miles through France and empties into the Atlantic at Nantes. Along its banks, you can discover some of the best wine values of the world. The Gros Plant will delight you, the Muscadet will bring joy to your holiday living, and the Pouilly- Blanc-Fume will provide depth of flavor, beautiful bouquet and sheer delight—all at a liveable price.

579 SAUVIGNON BLANC 1973............... 2.19 24.50 Here is the noble grape that produces Sauternes and Graves, and is often known in the Loire Valley as the Blanc-Fume which gives us Pouilly-Fume and Sancerre. Dry, light. Debreuil.

WHITE WINES FROM ALSACE

Gratifying indeed to the economy-minded wine lover, the ex- cellent dry white wines of Alsace have not followed the upward price graph of other areas of France. Buy them now while they are still bargains.

580 ALSATIAN SYLVANER 1971 (Muller).... 2.59 29.85 Light, blessed with a delicious flowery bouquet, rela- tively dry—here is a white wine that can be served freely because of low cost.

ALSATIAN RIESLING 1971 (Muller)...... 2.99 32.30 ‘Riesling’ is the noblest grape of the Rhine, Moselle and Alsace. In the skilled hands of Jules Muller, it achieves a high expression here.
